Net Positive Suction Head Available (NPSHA) — Derivation & Application
Overview
The formula for calculating Net Positive Suction Head Available is:
$$NPSH_A = H_{absolute} + H_{static} - H_{friction} - H_{vaporization}$$
Term	Description
$H_{absolute}$	Absolute pressure exerted on the fluid surface, expressed in meters of water
$H_{static}$	Pressure at the base of the fluid column due to the height of fluid, expressed in meters of water
$H_{friction}$	Pressure loss due to frictional losses in the piping system, expressed in meters of water
$H_{vaporization}$	Vapor pressure of the fluid, expressed in meters of water
---
Frictional Losses — Hagen–Poiseuille Equation
The frictional losses term $H_{friction}$ can be calculated using the Hagen–Poiseuille equation, assuming the fluid is in laminar flow and flowing through a vertical length of piping:
$$\Delta P = \frac{128 \mu L Q}{\pi D^4}$$
where:
$\mu$ — dynamic viscosity of the fluid $[\text{Pa·s}]$
$L$ — length of the pipe $[\text{m}]$
$Q$ — volumetric flow rate $[\text{m}^3/\text{s}]$
$D$ — pipe diameter $[\text{m}]$
---
Adaptation for a Conical Frustum
In the use case of interest, the Hagen–Poiseuille equation must be adapted for a conical frustum (a truncated cone).
Step 1 — Differential Form
First, express the Hagen–Poiseuille equation over a differential length $dz$ of piping:
$$dP = \frac{128 \mu Q}{\pi D(z)^4} , dz$$
or equivalently in terms of radius $r(z)$:
$$dP = \frac{8 \mu Q}{\pi r(z)^4} , dz$$
Step 2 — Radius as a Function of Position
For a frustum of length $L$ with inlet radius $r_1$ and outlet radius $r_2$, the radius varies linearly along the axial coordinate $z$:
$$r(z) = r_1 + \left(\frac{r_2 - r_1}{L}\right) z$$
Step 3 — Substitution
Substituting this expression into the differential form:
$$dP = \frac{8 \mu Q}{\pi \left[r_1 + \left(\dfrac{r_2 - r_1}{L}\right) z\right]^4} , dz$$
Step 4 — Integration over the Frustum Length
Integrating from $z = 0$ to $z = L$:
$$\Delta P = \frac{8 \mu Q}{\pi} \int_0^L \frac{dz}{\left[r_1 + \left(\dfrac{r_2 - r_1}{L}\right) z\right]^4}$$
Using the standard result $\displaystyle\int \frac{dz}{(a + bz)^4} = \frac{-1}{3b(a+bz)^3}$, with $a = r_1$ and $b = \dfrac{r_2 - r_1}{L}$:
$$\boxed{\Delta P_{frustum} = \frac{8 \mu Q L}{3\pi (r_2 - r_1)} \left(\frac{1}{r_1^3} - \frac{1}{r_2^3}\right)}$$
Converting to head of fluid (meters of water):
$$H_{friction} = \frac{\Delta P_{frustum}}{\rho g}$$
---
Calculating NPSHA
Now that the pressure drop through the frustum is known, calculating $NPSH_A$ is straightforward:
$$NPSH_A = H_{absolute} + H_{static} - \frac{\Delta P_{frustum}}{\rho g} - H_{vaporization}$$
---
Streamlit Application
The application presented here allows for easy determination of $NPSH_A$ as a function of several variables. Below are worked use cases.
Use Case — Viscous Polymer Solution from an Evaporator
In one particular project, the fluid was a highly viscous polymer solution leaving an evaporator. Given that the fluid was immediately leaving the evaporator, the fluid was in vapor–liquid equilibrium. This presents a special case where:
$$H_{absolute} = H_{vaporization}$$
These two terms cancel in the NPSHA equation, simplifying it to:
$$NPSH_A = H_{static} - H_{friction}$$
The user can then set:
Fluid viscosity $\mu$ — to reflect the polymer solution rheology
Desired volumetric flow rate $Q$ — to match the process requirement
The application then computes $NPSH_A$ and checks whether it exceeds the pump's required $NPSH_R$ with adequate margin, flagging conditions where cavitation risk is present.
